messages.content: Here he is.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: Well... at the very least, we've made it to this door. A final escape. What could lie on the other end? Death, despair? Life and hope abundant? Or merely more trials... let us find out.

author.name: v_entenmann
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\20b83a35b4910b5eb78d21e494ba8aac-2A6FD.png

messages.content: I walk out the door.

author.name: v_entenmann
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\20b83a35b4910b5eb78d21e494ba8aac-2A6FD.png

messages.content:
Viotto exits the palace, at last. The place still looks unusual, in some vague existential sense. A sky too bright, too off in hue. All those in the city are hidden away, all others further inside where he departed from.

The only person visible right outside is Magnolia, staring at this deceptive sky. ((End session))

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: She doesn't appear to have noticed his presence yet.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: Ah... I'm relieved to see her. I can't deny that it was absentminded of me to let her get ahead of us like that before. But now, things can continue.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I walk over. "Magnolia! What would you say is of interest in the heavens here?" I look up.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I can't tell whether the fact that it's hurting my eyes is just me.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “I don’t know. I doubt I have any insight you don’t.” She jolts slightly at Viotto’s voice, but doesn’t turn to him.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I wonder if I should have kept that map of the city.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "What were you hoping to accomplish here, then?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I shuffle my feet around a bit, nervous for some reason. The atmosphere here is unsettling...

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Nothing. There's nothing at all I can accomplish here. Don't you get it?"

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Yes, I think I understand. You feel defeated, of course... as many would in this situation. A strange place we're in, a lack of meaningful direction. But we must try, you know? Maybe it sounds like a bit of a generic motivational statement, but... in the end, the fact that I don't get it, as you say, is a factor in my favor."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I point towards a building. "Why not check in there?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: She turns to Viotto and her eyes narrow briefly. "You're still a man of faith, if I remember your words. Do you believe that hell exists?" This is a weird thing to say.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Yes, I do. Although, I'm of the doctrine that there are no unforgivable sins. Hell is a place meant to convince the prideful to finally repent, after a life of being denied that right. It's not permanent unless one chooses it to be so. Does that help with your question?" Whatever it is.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “That’s a bizarrely liberal view.” She looks at you slightly differently. “I don’t agree. If it’s real, I think it’s what lies past the point of persuasion. A place to maximize suffering. And I think that includes… all kinds.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "That seems reductive. It includes all kinds of suffering, yes, because it is the *ultimate* suffering. Everyone likely agrees on that. But that means that we can't really conceptualize what that would be like by relating it to any of our current feelings of distress. It's much like comparing ourselves to bugs - technically feasible, and, indeed, morally correct, but only useful to a very specific degree. I would be wary of what 'kinds' you wish to speak of here."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "After all, you seem to believe in something past the point of persuasion... a worrying ethic in practice."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “It doesn’t matter what I believe. The world is what it is regardless. I’m just saying that there’s some comfort in that idea, right? Or there would be. It’s why I guess I can understand that view of yours. Because if a sinner is past the point of no return, even as their organs are boiled and their minds tormented, some part of them can rest easy knowing there’s nothing to be done about it.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Why do you think the demons of Hell would have to resort to boiling somebody's organs? What I said about being unable to conceptualize it - that extends beyond emotional issues, and into physical means of suffering as well. God and his enemies are the very basis of the supernatural as we imagine it, after all. It's easy to invent flowery language to visualize the 'ultimate suffering', as I put it, but these are merely aids, not the truth of the matter. Their souls exist, and they are in infinite agony. There is no other action or state we need to invoke."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “My point was going to be that I don’t think people in hell get to understand that that’s where they are.” She shrugs. “But frankly, your description feels absurd in line with before. Who’s gonna be motivated to change by a state of infinite agony?”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Who isn't?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "I don't see your point, anyways. I assume you're saying that this city is Hell? Magnolia, dear, if you're right about the fact that people in Hell aren't allowed the understanding of their existence in it, how could you possibly think that you've worked it out? The moment you came to the conclusion, it would be disproven. You don't get to circumvent the rules of your own logic merely because you're struggling."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Please, just let me know if there's anything I can do to alleviate it."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “A catch-22, yeah. I thought of that. Not sure how to resolve it.  But anyway… No one would be motivated to change by senseless and aimless torment. In the real world, torture just gets people to blurt out any confession or statement they think will make it stop for even the briefest of moments. It’d be like that. They’d try to think of how to make it seem like they’d changed. If hell served the purpose you’re talking about, I’d imagine something closer to like… Dante’s Inferno. The dumb ironic punishments for different varieties of sinner.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "What makes you believe you would be capable of lying in Hell?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “If God was willing to prevent that, why would hell even exist? The entire reason he allows suffering is supposed to be for the sake of free will. If he puts them on a track where they can do nothing *but* redeem themselves, what was the point of any of it?”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "They are not forced to redeem themselves. They can continue suffering. A lack of redemption leads to suffering here as well. Do you think that violates free will?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "What do you think free will is, if not allowing us the choice to continue suffering? Perhaps you've gotten cause and effect mixed up."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “Why would they be prevented from lying? What would be the point of that? It wouldn’t be a conscious lie, anyway. People can believe they’re good and be wrong.” She looks back up at the sky. “I don’t, anyway, so that’s irrelevant. I don’t need to lie to be like this.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Why do you think somebody would be able to get out of Hell simply by claiming that they're good? Is that what repentance is to you? Self-aggrandization? I wouldn't think..."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "...be like what?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I squint at her.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
“I don’t. I’m saying the exact opposite. That they wouldn’t be able to escape because that’s all they’d ever try to do, and obviously that wouldn’t result in anything. That’s the *entire* crux of my argument, of this whole line of questioning. God, what the hell— what is this? Have you ever actually *listened* to someone else in your entire life? Or do you just pick up enough keywords to form whatever sentence you want to be able to hear yourself talk with, like some child phoning in their book report.”

She pauses long enough for Viotto to maybe start saying something, and then keeps talking anyway. “Which is fine.
I’m in no place to judge. I’m the exact same. Not once, a single time, have I ever put in enough effort to understand anything about you. I didn’t understand my daughter either. I don’t think I really knew my husband past a surface level. I don’t get to know other people. But I know one thing about you now.”

She looks back at you and smiles slightly. “I went through the most aimless torment imaginable. With some help from my parents. It never made me stronger, or a better person. It made me paranoid. It made me stubborn. It made me condescending, and clueless, and alone. It made me constantly speak over anyone I thought I was above or knew better than. It made me like *you*.”
She laughs. “It really took me so long to realize.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content:
"Well, I'm glad I could be of some help during your torment, at least."
He smiles.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
“We really do fucking deserve each other.”

The ground shakes slightly. The sky shifts. It looks, for a moment, as if all of existence is under the floorboards of some building. Then it returns to what it looked like prior.

“I don’t even care anymore. Things are just going to keep happening randomly until I die. Haha!”

((End chapter))

author.name: scipe

author.name: scipe

messages.content: He stumbles a bit at the tremor, but catches himself and looks over at her. "Did you see that?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Sure, something happened to the sky, or whatever. Magic is real here, so anything goes! Great."

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "That seems... defeatist, Mag. Do you not believe the universe is capable of being understood? Do you not truly believe that events have cause, effect, meaning? And if not, why did we have this conversation at all? I don't accept that you think that, at least not on any subconscious level. Anything does not go."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Except, perhaps, us."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "...we ought to go somewhere. Oughtn't we?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "...Sure." She shrugs.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "You said that there wasn't anything we could accomplish here. What encompasses 'here'? The city? The... country? The world?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: He wonders if this place is civilized enough to have countries.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “Sure? I only half understand where we are, but it’s not…” She looks around. “Home.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Believing that you can only accomplish things inside your own home is the mindset of a recluse. It is how you become trapped, endlessly confined by the things that you believe to be expected of you. It helps you achieve none of your goals... real change is only effected by being out in the real world. And, here we are."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "I don't accept your framing, anyways." He looks around for any landmarks besides the palace.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

Magnolia.

“The ones we walked past?” She rolls her eyes. “No, I’m not… I’m fine.”

Magnolia slumps against the wall of a house that seems pretty shoddy in its construction. This is likely a poorer area, just looking at it.

messages.content:
"I... don't care."

...Really? This is going nowhere fast. I thought there'd at least be... something.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Then why did you roll your eyes?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

author.name: scipe

messages.content: "Unless you have some nebulous definition of 'care', where you must like something to care about it... in which case, how have you navigated this world? What goals have you been working towards, Magnolia? Now feels like the proper time to work it out, if you feel aimless. But please do keep in mind that disdain is tied to investment."

messages.content: "But what about you? Where is the line drawn between your desires and your actions?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "I don't understand what you mean."

The building arbitrarily collapses. No one can stop that from happening. Not anymore. It's possible. Accidents happen all the time. This whole city has had chaos unfold through it. Or maybe it was something else. Maybe a monster came by and wreaked havoc. A big bad wolf knocked this house down.

Viotto can react to this, but not very effectively. His leg is pinned by a piece of rubble as he dodges out of the way. Magnolia is less lucky. Her abdomen is pierced through by a support beam. She is not going to make it. Not this version of her, at least.

"Gh..." She coughs up blood.

He flips arduously to a page near the end, occasionally glancing back up into Magnolia's eyes.
"I am... I am not blind... to my ideology. I know its presence. My life..."
He looks back up at her again, his eyes blurring. He quickly glances down again.
"My life has been built around one idea... course correction, you could call it..."
The paper is shifting.
"When we speak into this world... do we expect our outcries to be met... with universal compliance? Or... do we choose people for a quality they alone possess...? If... if..."
...
"If this were my confession..."
...
...

messages.content:
My eyes focus back on one line in my notes, an inch from the bridge of my nose.

messages.content: Viotto awakens on a bed staring at an unfamiliar ceiling.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I lay there silently for a few moments, before tears start running down my face. I can't do anything to stop them. Why doesn't it ever end? Why can I not stop losing them? The moment just replays in my head, over and over again. The most banal form of grief. And I can't even stand that.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: It begins to feel like something is moving around inside of me, some kind of snake twisting itself back and forth just underneath my skin. But moving my arm to swat at it would be more effort than it's worth.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: But there's something shifting inside my head, too, and I can do much less to stop myself from confronting that.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: It's like, before... the back half of my brain was filled with TV static, and the front half was habitable. And now, they've suddenly switched. The front half is unbearable to put myself into. And I keep trying to drag myself to the back, this new space I have to live in, but... there's some kind of intense homesickness I now have for the front. I know I can't survive there, not at the moment. But I feel as if my blood has stopped flowing, and there's an ice bath sitting just next to me, ready to restart the circulation. That disgusting pull of the shock.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I can only miss a state of mind, and nothing more specific.

Viotto isn’t talking to anyone. No one wants anything from him. I guess his being here means at least one person does, but whatever.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

She lets you do this.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "No, no, that's not true. There was no mandate for this, I swear. The plans of the world... are measured in length, not order."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "We should... get out of here."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “…What does that even mean? Length? What’s next, width and height? I don’t think there’s a plan.” She scratches her head. “I’ve spent a long time balancing an underlying belief in a higher power with perception of meaninglessness around me, and I think the answer is that aimlessness is His punishment. The consequence is to be left alone. You get what you ask for.” She coughs. “…That said, I guess we can try leaving. This place is creepy. I just want to make sure that old man isn’t fuckin’ dead first.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: Zaquera was stabbed in the chest area. It missed his heart, but the wound certainly isn’t trivial. I don’t know how much a fucking veterinarian can do here, you tell me.

“…Viotto Entenmann?” The cop asks this.

messages.content:
The cop swiftly cuffs Viotto. “No, you’re under arrest. You’re already a fugitive, but your presence has been deemed necessary. …For whatever reason.”

“Hey, let him go!” Magnolia says this, and then makes a weird expression.

messages.content:
Viotto wakes up.

He is in a hallway, handcuffed to a pipe sticking out of the wall. Zaquera and Rikarasu are here and similarly restrained; the latter is unconscious and will not be waking up any time soon.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content:
I instinctively try to stand up, snapping my wrist painfully against the cuff before I notice it. 
Oh. I see. What did she say? That I was... necessary? No, somehow I doubt that I'd like to find out what that means to a person such as her... but I just don't think I have a realistic way out of here, do I?

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I turn to Zaquera. "I don't suppose you would happen to have a lockpicking kit on your person?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “It was not an eventuality I prepared for, no.” He looks down, sullen. “I have no intention to run, anyway. I would be found. I have a better chance with these people than others who want my head.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Well, that being the case doesn't entitle you to make me share in your circumstances. I have no chance at all with 'these people'... they'll take away every freedom I've ever had, or worse, force upon me ones I've never wanted. There must be a way out of here."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "What's his name again?" I flick my head at the other person here.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “Zaquera Culbasko.” Zaquera Culbasko says this.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "What's your name?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I sigh. "What is the name of the unconscious person?"

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “That is Rikarasu Endo.” Zaquera identifies Rikarasu Endo.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "I see. RIKARASU!" I shout the name.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
This doesn’t work.

Magnolia arrives, walking briskly across the hall. “A-Are you okay?”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: A bit of tension releases in my head. "No, no, I'm absolutely not fine. I need to get out of here before she comes back... help me!"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I jangle the cuff exasperatedly.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
“……”
Magnolia stares at you. Her expression shifts. Her eyes scan the area. She seems like she’s about to say something a few times, but keeps stopping herself. She settles on this:
“Why?”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: Well, I said three things just now, but technically they all have the same answer. I thought I made it pretty apparent with the aforementioned jangling.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Is that a philosophical question?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “Only in the sense everything is.” She puts a hand to her hip.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "I see. We're having this kind of conversation."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “You only ever really have one type of conversation.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "But you're not me. And so, you can understand why I would doubt your sincerity in it."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Do you have a lockpick?"

messages.content: “We’re in a secluded facility inside a frozen wasteland. Where are you going to run? Or do you plan to hijack a vehicle at some point? I thought your ideals precluded that kind of thing.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Ideals that would prevent me from saving my own life, or the life of another, would be no ideals at all. Everything has its limit, as I'm sure you've found on this long journey of yours..."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Would you hurl such an accusation at me if I were a climate activist who protested against the use of the same vehicles, or is the fringeness of my ideas the only thing that makes me so questionable to you? Something to think about while you help me out of here."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
“No, you’re right. I couldn’t agree more. Every ideal has its breaking point. Here’s mine.” She shrugs.
“I died, Viotto. That was finally enough to shake me into realizing I really don’t want to. There’s still someone who needs me. Maybe even more than one person.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: “Don’t flatter yourself.” She looks away. “…I guess it’s thanks to you. In an insane way. So this isn’t as easy as I’d like.”

messages.content:
“There’s no *need* to say anything to you, but I still tried.” She scratches the back of her neck. “…I’m a felon, right now, but I’ve been offered a sort of amnesty for extenuating circumstances. All I have to do is not screw anything up going forward. …And, if needed, testify against you. It seemed like something thrown in there, and I do hope they don’t have to resort to that. …But if they do, well… I’m not going to let you drag me down with you.” 
She stares at you, expressionless. “I’m abandoning you. Maybe that’ll make us even.”

messages.content: He looks down at the floor mournfully for a few moments. But then, his head snaps up. His gaze bores into her.

author.name: v_entenmann
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\20b83a35b4910b5eb78d21e494ba8aac-2A6FD.png

messages.content: "I understand. Was it always this with you? Petty revenge for some perceived failing? So that pain begets pain. That, that is where your ideals have led you...? You know, Magnolia, in all the time we've been together, there's been one thing I've been searching for from you, and it's fairly simple. A set of principles! I wished to believe that you had found your own way of navigating life, that you processed the world in a way befitting of somebody who walks through it with such confidence. And even here, you tell me that you are reaching the breaking point of some ideal comparable to mine... ha. And what ideal would that be? The ideal of narcissistically carting me around like some dog on its way to the pound? You think you'll find catharsis through the legal system, through the courts? You think you'll finally be rid of me? You won't! Not in the way you want, not in the way you're looking for. Your affirmation is 'thanks to me'? Don't fool yourself! Everything you've ever been through is thanks to me, your entire life is thanks to me! That's the miracle of birth, something I can tell you firsthand that the world does not treat with respect. We've gone from mangers to cribs... and in all that time, what has changed? Only the practical design, with symbolic hay kindling transforming into a literal barred cage of wood! How pointed can the world get? The fires licking around the edges of our infantile vision... that is the life you lead now, as you hope to turn me into the symbolic sacrifice to absolve you of your sins. Oh, Judas... I see the way your eye wanders, the way it flicks in envy! But can you truly find it in yourself to abandon the one who has come back from his isolation to help you in your time of need? I know you are not an unwilling person, Magnolia, I can see how hard you try! Trust me on this, the demons of this world are those who commit atrocity without hesitation. And you hesitate... that is what sets you apart from others, that is what enables you to exercise your free will productively. You want people to be happy, but you struggle to find the path, as we all do... that is the point of companionship, that is the meaning of our bond. It has taken me so long to see that, but I see it now, I have been sent through these trials to develop my sense of intimacy… no man can go it alone, no man can evolve without an exchange of ideas. I have stepped out of my enclosure, for you! It has been for you, all for you, I have put in the time and the effort, the backbreaking effort, and you appreciate none of it! You look down on me, you deceive me, you leave me behind in my hour of need!"

author.name: v_entenmann
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\20b83a35b4910b5eb78d21e494ba8aac-2A6FD.png

messages.content: "And yet, I know where this leads… and so, of course, should you. You say you will do to me what I did to you… in that case, do you believe me to be perfect? After all, you seem intent on modeling yourself after me, or some envisioned version of why I did the things I did, consequences divorced from causes divorced from effects. You see me as some kind of shining figure, off on that distant hill… so far away, and yet close enough to peer into my soul and pass judgment, in your own pitying gaze. As if you have some quality that you alone possess. This everlasting framing, throughout human history and all its tidings! And yet you don't know what you want any more than I, do you? I speak of hesitation, but that cannot be an endless state of existence... nobody can hesitate forever. Once, twice, you hold yourself back and you've proven your consideration, but after that, no more, I say! But you, no, you're a true reactionary! Starting everything and following through on nothing. A sense of dedication only to assuaging any temporary emotional state you find yourself in, or some sense of cosmic fairness, evenness, as you say. An armchair philosopher, up until the very last moment, the moment we find ourselves in! Fine! Let us go through with it... see where this leads us, see where we go from here, where we will all end up. But let it not be said that I haven't warned you, in clear terms spoken with clear eyes. There is no coming back from this. Someday, you will stand in discernment. And I will not be there."

author.name: v_entenmann
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\20b83a35b4910b5eb78d21e494ba8aac-2A6FD.png

messages.content:
Okay, I guess she sits here as you say all of this completely meaningless fucking garbage. Magnolia is probably going to soften the blow, but just know that you’re actual scum, and you should really try killing yourself as soon as your hands are free. Maybe they’ll be able to make use of you then, selling your organs or something. But you won’t.

She chuckles. “I know. I’ll never be free of you. I never have been. You didn’t come back for me. Not just in the literal sense. But you never left. Your presence…” She trails off. “Well, I’ll see you around. If not in discernment. Whatever that means.”

messages.content:
Eventually, the cop returns. 
“Mr. Entenmann. I know your ilk are incapable of listening to reason, but I will say it anyway. I am bringing you in as a witness who may speak on the murder of Sheeval Deltent. This is a trial being carried out covertly, outside of the jurisdiction of any one government. You will not have a lawyer to nitpick about the mistreatment of your rights. I cannot kill you, but I can do anything else. I stopped by while dropping off Rikarasu to ensure I was properly supplied for this, because your reputation precedes you. If you attempt to run, I will electrocute you until you begin foaming at the mouth. If you attempt to break out of the handcuffs, or do some nonsense you’ve seen in a movie like dislocate your thumb to slip out, I will electrocute you until you begin foaming at the mouth. If you attempt to injure me, I will electrocute you until you begin foaming at the mouth. If you attempt to scream or be otherwise disruptive…” She stares at you.

She leads Viotto through the hall to a dodecagonal room. After typing something on a computer in this room, she leaves it.

…I’m not describing the entire process of locomotion in detail. Perhaps you resist and she easily quells this. Viotto is eventually brought to something resembling a courtroom, and directed to a seating area to the side. There’s a small handful of people here; men in suits, those positioned to play the role of security, someone in the position of a judge, a handful of others in the space where Viotto is sitting.

The cop sighs. “…You’re not my problem anymore. Have fun.” She walks away.

messages.content: "Can I... go wait outside, then?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
“No.” He proceeds to ignore Viotto.

“Hey.” A man next to Viotto whispers. “I only half know what’s going on, but it’s probably best to just let the big man take the fall for everything. Keep quiet where ya can. They probably aren’t gonna go after us little guys if they feel they have their culprit or whatever.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I respond at a normal volume. "If I am so utterly unimportant, why did they nearly kill me in their attempt to bring me here? There are people out there who were willing to put their jobs on the line to make certain my presence. Maybe you mean nothing, but no, my friend, that is not a universal experience."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “Damn. I guess I don’t know who you are. Sorry, I suppose.” This is the worst line in The Antarctica Project. It’s unfortunate that not everyone knows how to rightfully treat Viotto the way Kyros does, which isn’t a name he knows but whatever.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Clearly." I sit next to him.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "My name is... Viotto."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “I’m Bill Seminario.” This isn’t a real character that exists.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: No, he definitely is. "What are you here to testify on, Seminario?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Were you there when my friend passed?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “…Uh, no, nobody… well, one guy died, but I don’t think that’s what I’m supposed to testify about. I’m here to talk about, like… the internal operations of the project he worked on? I wasn’t hired for this until recently, honestly, but I did some logistics in terms of …setup? Like, he wanted a room to be guarded in case of some eventuality that didn’t matter, so I stand there. Or he wants food and drink prepared for the final room his participants end up in, so I help with that. Little bit weird, but…. Take what you can get in this economy, you know?” He scratches his head. “I’m not sure why I’m here. I think they’re just trying to minimize bringing in anyone who doesn’t already know about this guy.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "I don't remember there being any food. At the very least, none was served to me. I think you did a poor job."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “I see. Well, I’m definitely unemployed now, so it is what it is.” There was food there. The explicitly noted refreshments. I wonder if you are senile or merely a sadist? Has Magnolia’s ability to try living led Viotto to realize passive cruelty is no longer sufficient? Does he simply hate Billy Seminario? We can only speculate. Bill shrugs.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "You're right. It is what it is. Tautology keeps us all going, doesn't it? I think I may have been taught a lesson on that recently." I say it bitterly, of course.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "How long do we have to... wait?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “I dunno. Probably til they bring him out. …And then until they’re done with whatever they’re gonna try him for.” Billy, who at no point claimed that directly serving food was his job or even an expectation set by anyone, says this.

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I call out to the judge. "Is there any way I can assist in this process?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Is there a hold-up?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
The Judge doesn’t respond.

The cop from earlier brings Zaquera in and puts him at the stand.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: Oh, okay. I wonder if Rikarasu's rotting corpse will also appear. Ha.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I start tapping my foot in an uneven rhythm.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
Whatever.

The Judge clears his throat. “Mr. Zaquera Culbasko.”

He nods. “Yes.”

“Born—”

Zaquera interrupts the judge. “We don’t need to iterate over my life story. I’m cooperating with your accusations. Let us get it over with.”

“…Respectfully, you do not dictate the pace of these proceedings.”

“No, but that was a polite suggestion. As you were.”

The Judge sighs. “You stand here accused of, as an overview, conspiracy to commit offense and defraud, a dozen — to our knowledge — instances of kidnapping, misappropriation of intrafederal and interfederal resources, tax evasion, and multiple cases of manslaughter, the severity or intentionality of which are still being evaluated. These crimes span over 17 different countries, which is what, in addition to the classified nature of some of your crimes, is forcing us to take unorthodox means in holding you accountable. Does all of this sound correct? Do you acknowledge the charges brought against you?”

He squints, staring at the floor.
“…Seventeen? I don’t feel like it was ever that. I’d expect a smaller number. You must be counting some niche cases.” Zaquera looks back up. “Yes, at any rate. That probably all checks out. I plead guilty, if that set of terminology still applies in whatever context this is.”

The judge proceeds to list off the specifics of a variety of acts Zaquera is accused of, with the man responding with brief confirmation or a small technical correction. No one else is involved in this process, which is rather bizarre.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I raise my hand. "What was he born as?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
No one acknowledges Viotto. Actually, maybe his birth name, Hideo Kuina, comes up during the list of crimes and their descriptions. We can say it does. So the question doesn’t even matter, at any rate.

The Judge lists of the names of those Zaquera is responsible, indirectly, for kidnapping and bringing to either the continent of Antarctica or elsewhere. There’s names Viotto would recognize, being himself, the other participants, people like Magnolia. A few he doesn’t. Some guy named Richard Ogden.

“I would take semantic issue with calling it kidnapping. In principle, though, what you allege I have done is accurate. …Though I would note within the web of international laws, you could probably put up a decent defense for the girl I have some legal custody over.” Zaquera shrugs.

The Judge, obviously having prepared for this, explains the wide variety of felonies and legally improper actions that he implicitly took by negligence in how Erica Furuda’s childhood transpired.

Zaquera smirks wryly. “…Yeah, alright. I wonder how you know in such detail…? How can I trust that information is accurate?”

“…The source for this account was provided by a former employee of yours, Sharona Erveza.”

Zaquera chuckles. “Right, of course. My loyal employees.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I try to chime in again. "Why is she considered such a trustworthy source that you can build a complex legal case off of her word? Did she prove paperwork, video, anything? Or just spiteful accusations?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I look over to Zaquera comfortingly.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
“…I agree, this is something worth clarifying. I just think I already know the answer.” Zaquera rolls his eyes.

The judge actually bothers with this one. “Erveza was merely the initial source to bring this to our attention. The dossier involved written records from Zaquera itself, recorded video or audio of relevant conversations, documents or forged paperwork to feign compliance with different national policies, as well as personally corroborated testimony from others that had interacted with at least one of Zaquera or his daughter.” The Judge.

“Yeah, see?” Zaquera glances at Viotto. “The bitch is thorough. Inhumanly so. But this is all tangential to why I’m actually here. Please don’t pretend you people care about her well-being any more than I do.”

The Judge sifts through paperwork for a moment.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "I agree."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I tune out of the proceedings, and try to casually make my way over to Zaquera so we can converse.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
True?
Viotto is held back by a bailiff, obviously. By force, if necessary.

“…I will now iterate over the list of those who are dead or presumed dead as a result of your actions.” The Judge looks over a document. “James Adair. Lydia Meda. Hosni al-Shafei.”
He lists a fair amount of names, most of which Viotto does not recognize. Perhaps there’s a familiar surname in there. Zaquera sits through this silently, occasionally nodding or tilting his head.

“…Julio DeChai. Maria Sanchez. Sheeval Deltent. Ganna Oppin—”


“No.” Zaquera interrupts.

“…Hm?” The judge looks up.

“I didn’t kill Sheeval. …I wasn’t at fault for Ganna either — she’s not really dead and what she is she did to herself — but I at least understand where you’re probably coming from there. I had nothing to do with what happened to Sheeval. I did not kill him.”

The Judge narrows his eyes. “Bear in mind that we are not alleging you personally murdered the man. He was merely another casualty of one of your endeavors, a death on your orders.”

“He wasn’t.” Zaquera shakes his head. “I don’t know what happened to him. I mourn his loss every day. I would never wish harm to the one person who has supported me in my life.” He says all this emotionlessly. “Strike that one from the record so we can continue.”

The Judge sighs, sifting through papers again. “…who are the relevant witnesses for him…”

“…It’s him.” The cop gestures towards Viotto. “We can… deal with the Oppineta thing if we have to. But the person brought in for Deltent’s case is Viotto Entenmann.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I slowly get to my feet. "Is it time for me... to testify?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “…Yes.” The Judge nods. “In particular, about what you remember regarding the circumstances of Sheeval Deltent’s death.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I walk to the stand.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: Is there a microphone?

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: Sure.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content:
I eye it nervously, and choose to push it slightly further away.
"Honorable judge, honorable court... I stand here to tell you one thing, and one thing only. It is simple and short. Sheeval Deltent committed suicide. I was the recipient of his note, although I am no longer able to provide the original copy of it, as my belongings have been systematically stripped from me over time. By operatives of this man, perhaps. I have no interest in portraying him as a good person. But he says he is innocent of this, and I believe him."
"...And yet, Zaquera... do you truly believe that letting them put you down like this allows you to find atonement? I'm familiar with the idea that suffering brings redemption, of course, I have defaulted to framing my own choices like that when I am at my lowest and lose sight of their other meanings. But how can you claim ownership over that redemption if you are not in control of it, if it is kept shackled by those other than you? Does this... feel right to you? I need... to know."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
“It does not matter.” Zaquera shakes his head. “There is no path to atonement. There has not been for some time. I don’t care about that.”

“…The numerous wounds Sheeval was found with are rather inexplicable under an answer of suicide.”

“…What of the woman with him?” Zaquera asks.

“…What?”

“Another body in the same place as Sheeval’s. Unidentified, at the time at least. I read about the circumstances of his death. What motive would I have for her?”

“I have been made aware of no such thing.” The Judge shakes his head.

“He’s just trying to muddle things.” The cop mutters.

“I am not crazy.” Zaquera.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "It's certainly possible that he lacked the strength to follow through on his own threat, and so he instigated a conflict with somebody to offload the responsibility onto them. Either way, this man would be uninvolved."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: Or, perhaps he realized the impermissibility of it. I don't actually believe that this is what happened to him, regardless. But I do hold some hope that he made peace with the world in his final moments. That's not wrong of me.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: He was a good man.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: Or, he tried to be.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: But there are more good men left.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
“That’s exactly it. There’s something completely overlooked in that case! He’s — why would I have done that?! Everything attributed to me served some purpose, some misguided goal. I don’t stab people in an alley, leave them for the worms to consume. What else are you pinning on me?? Let me see. Let me see that damned list!” Zaquera walks out from behind the stand. A bailiff restrains him. “I didn’t kill him! Do you hear me?!”

“This is a trivial matter. It can be investigated further to confirm how Sheeval’s final moments related to you. You were the reason he was there at all, weren’t you? It is rather unusual without context, but with the context of your involvement…”
The judge muses.

“There was no involvement…!”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Everyone who ever had an impact on Sheeval's life was in some sense responsible for him being there. Everyone in the world had some effect on that. We live as part of a complete whole. Are we all charged with this murder? Am I? How far are you willing to go, arbiter? How entitled are you to this judgment?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Find it in yourself to end this cruelty... please. I beg of you."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
“I am obviously not concerned with philosophy. Culbasko’s culpability in these matters is far more tangible…” The judge explains.

Zaquera elbows the bailiff in the face and topples over. He scampers to his feet and is caught again. Blood seeps through his shirt, the wound having reopened. He screams.

The judge sighs. “…We will adjourn for the moment.”

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Is there a medical station nearby? May I get treatment for my wounds as well?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “Are you wounded? I don’t see why not, then.” The judge.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "Yes. My wrist has been shattered by the woman who brought me in."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "It was unnecessary."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "But, anyways, thank you."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I follow after wherever they might take Zaquera.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
This happens. A small handful of medical professionals in the room see to Zaquera’s condition. A singular man checks over Viotto.

He checks Viotto’s wrist. “…It’s not broken. Simply sprained.” He does the thing that would be done to treat and address this.

The cop enters. “You can leave, incidentally. They’ve confirmed that’s all they wanted from you. Somehow.” She glares at Viotto.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I wave my wrist brace at her. "No, I'll be going back. I don't trust that they'll proceed fairly without a neutral observer. It's my ethical responsibility. It's too late to get out now."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “That’s… great.” She seethes. “Good luck with that.” She exits the room without breaking anything.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I watch her leave. What a sad, angry woman. As should be expected, I suppose.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: But I get up, and head back to the courtroom.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content:
Viotto is in the courtroom of his own free will, after all that time being a little bitch about getting dragged here. I guess I can kind of be on his side for this one, since I don’t really support police brutality on principle. So it’s pretty funny that she gets so mad about this.

I guess the ideal world is one where Viotto only ever interacts with horrible people. Maybe we aren’t that far off from there.

Anyway, proceedings haven’t resumed yet, since Zaquera is still in the middle of bleeding to death a little.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: I look up at the judge. "Why are you in this line of work, if I may ask? Does it bring you pleasure, or is it a more rote career choice?"

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "I think I would find it hard to end up viewing everything in my life through a lens of... judgment, for lack of a better word. I could never decide what people deserve. Personally speaking, of course."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: "Maybe some would consider that a failing."

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: “You really aren’t supposed to just talk to me.” No one else seems to be paying attention to this, though. The judge, who isn’t a real character that exists either, answers. “…This isn’t exactly within the scope of my normal responsibilities. But a role needed to be filled. …I have studied international law in my life when its more local counterpart proved stifling. Perhaps it was a consequence of the smallness of my home country, but it all felt a bit trivial, laden with biases. It did not satisfy my youthful ideals of justice. The truth, I felt, was only achieved through viewing from multiple angles. Perhaps the role of a judge is a natural extension of that.”

author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content: "And, why would an international judge be subject to fewer biases, and more angles, than a local one? Surely the role is the same either way... to bring things closer to the truth, regardless of that effort's source..."

messages.content: "I'd say that... the only difference is, as you mention, the scope. The burden of responsibility. What part of you wishes for that burden, do you suppose?"

Unless you trust him and his judgment, of course."

messages.content:
It does. Most of it is tedious. A lot of lore nonsense, a lot of minutiae. Not worth transcribing all of. Though presumably the stenographer did. If whatever this is has one. Zaquera manages to stay alive long enough for them to hit him with all of it. He says very little. It seems that last outburst, or its subject matter, killed his spirit and will to be snarky about accepting everything they accuse him of. Obviously nothing Viotto says past this point matters either. 

Zaquera stands trial before a special council. He is judged. His silence is sworn, though it won’t matter. He is given multiple life sentences, which he obviously won’t come close to living out one of.

Who cares, really. Great question. He doesn’t receive the death penalty. Maybe they don’t have protocol or the ability to do that. Perhaps it’s judged as too good for him.

Zaquera Culbasko is taken away. All others trickle out of here, ready to depart via limo or bicycle or some secret other method. Viotto Entenmann is, against all odds, a free man. Because he too does not deserve to die right now.

author.name: scipe
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\0a858383a5c98e5e573e49bf3f2bdbe1-9F159.png

messages.content:
I found it hard to pay attention to most of the trial beyond this point, but the outcome saddens me nonetheless. It weighs on me, that I lacked the ability to help. These institutions are ones that force themselves on you, they are nothing but endless boxes to shove people into, and that has always been why I've endeavored to stay away from them. Just once, I broke my rule, and it has amounted to nothing but... boredom, really. An unsatisfying distraction. I could not truly take my mind off of... what I wanted to. I can still feel it. I can still feel the difficulty I have drawing in breath, the haze that hovers behind my eyes, the abscess eating away at my stomach, the pins and needles running circles through my chest, the pervasive numbness, the pervasive pain, the feeling of wear and age and exhaustion and the feeling of nothing. I haven't left anything behind yet. 
But, I tried. Not as hard as I have tried at some things, but it was a losing battle. The trial, that is. And it meant very little to me, in the end. It doesn't weigh on me, knowing that I never truly had the ability to help. And I can go on.

author.name: bloopiero
author.avatarUrl: C:\Users\Aidan\Documents\TAP Reading Order\json version\ASSETS forma de json\d99c460ae22eacecb7185aae4c31f492-452CA.png

messages.content: I don't deserve to die right now. And so, I look around the courtroom one more time, and I leave.
